Integration test for `steno`'s smart-profile renderer, ported from `test/smart.test.ts`; exercises `render_smart` against real entries expanded from the repo's root `dict.steno` corpus, plus `build_smart_dict` for the full-dictionary build.

The corpus is read live via `corpus()` (`concat!(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"), "/../../dict.steno")`), so tests fail if that file moves or the referenced strokes (`STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-BGS`, `STKWR-T/PR/STR`, `STKWRUPBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-PBGS/PR-FLT`, `STKWR-RBGT/S`, `STKWR-RBGT/HR`, `STKWR-RPBT`) are renamed or removed in `dict.steno`. All corpus-dependent tests silently no-op via `.unwrap()` on `Option`/`Result` if the file can't be read or parsed — they'll panic, not skip, so a missing corpus fails loudly rather than quietly passing.

The `STKWR-LT` stroke was repurposed upstream (now a `let` binding) and no longer matches the original TS fixture's `` `${%0}` `` template-literal case. Rather than dropping that coverage, `template_literal()` synthesizes a standalone `TypedEntry` directly via `parse_template` + manual `Entry`/`TypedEntry` construction (through `terminal_entry`), bypassing the corpus entirely for that one case. Anyone editing `TypedEntry`, `Entry`, or `EntryFlags`'s field layout must update `terminal_entry`'s manual construction in lockstep, since it's the one place in this test file (and possibly the codebase) hand-building these structs rather than going through `parse_source`/`expand_dict`.

Key assertions worth knowing about if touching the smart renderer: functions drop the trailing `}` but keep interior `)` (auto-close/type-over semantics), index `[` drops trailing `]`, generics keep both `<`/`>` (since `<` isn't auto-closed), `@literal` blocks route through a "v2 struct emitter" that never types closing braces (uses `{#Down...}` navigation instead) while `render_plain` always types every brace — so smart and plain output must differ for those two strokes specifically. Non-terminal entries and bracket-free constructs (ternaries) must render byte-identical between `render_smart` and `render_plain`. `full_smart_dict` asserts zero collisions and more than 1000 resulting keys — a strong regression signal if the corpus or renderer logic changes entry counts.